# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amherst-college
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ***Academic Ranking of World Universities*** (***ARWU***), also known as the **Shanghai Ranking**, is one of the annual publications of world university rankings.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The league table was originally compiled and issued by Shanghai Jiao Tong University in 2003, making it the first global university ranking with multifarious indicators.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Since 2009, *ARWU* has been published and copyrighted annually by Shanghai Ranking Consultancy, an organization focusing on higher education that is not legally subordinated to any universities or government agencies.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] In 2011, a board of international advisory consisting of scholars and policy researchers was established to provide suggestions.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The publication currently includes global league tables for institutions as a whole and for a selection of individual subjects, alongside independent regional *Greater China Ranking* and *Macedonian HEIs Ranking*.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Altbach named ARWU's 'consistency, clarity of purpose, and transparency' as significant strengths.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] University of Oxford Chancellor Chris Patten has said "the methodology looks fairly solid ... it looks like a pretty good stab at a fair comparison." While ARWU has originated in China, the ranking have been praised for being unbiased towards Asian institutions, especially Chinese institutions.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The ranking has been criticised for "relying too much on award factors" thus undermining the importance of quality of instruction and humanities.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2007 paper published in the journal *Scientometrics* found that the results from the Shanghai rankings could not be reproduced from raw data using the method described by Liu and Cheng.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] A 2013 paper in the same journal finally showed how the Shanghai ranking results could be reproduced.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Vincke analyse how the ARWU works, using their insights as specialists of Multiple Criteria Decision Making (MCDM).
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Their main conclusions are that the criteria used are not relevant; that the aggregation methodology has a number of major problems; and that insufficient attention has been paid to fundamental choices of criteria.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Cheng, think that the quality of universities cannot be precisely measured by mere numbers and any ranking must be controversial.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They suggest that university and college rankings should be used with caution and their methodologies must be understood clearly before reporting or using the results.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] *ARWU* has been criticised by the European Commission as well as some EU member states for "favour[ing] Anglo-Saxon higher education institutions".
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] For instance, *ARWU* is repeatedly criticised in France, where it triggers an annual controversy, focusing on its ill-adapted character to the French academic system and the unreasonable weight given to research often performed decades ago.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] It is also criticised in France for its use as a motivation for merging universities into larger ones.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Several methods for ranking universities were analyzed.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Many scholars proposed developing new methodologies for global university rankings, expressing concerns about bias against universities in the Arab region within current ranking systems.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] They emphasized the need to adjust the weighting of indicators to account for overlooked institutional differences.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] There are two categories in *ARWU'*s disciplinary rankings: broad subject fields and specific subjects.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] The methodology is similar to that adopted in the overall table, including award factors, paper citation, and the number of highly cited scholars.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Considering the development of specific areas, two independent regional league tables with different methodologies were launched – Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China and Best Chinese Universities Ranking.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Best Chinese Universities Ranking was first released in 2015.
[src:amherst-college/academic-ranking-of-world-universities] Ranking of Top Universities in Greater China was first released in 2011.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The **Academy Awards**, more commonly known as the **Oscars**, are awards based on artistic and technical merit in film.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] They are presented annually by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS) in the United States in recognition of excellence in cinematic achievements, as assessed by the Academy's voting membership.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Oscars are widely considered to be the most prestigious awards in the American film industry, predominantly centered around films produced in Hollywood.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The major award categories, known as the **Academy Awards of Merit**, are presented during a live televised Hollywood ceremony in February or March.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It is the longest running worldwide entertainment awards ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 1st Academy Awards were held in 1929.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The second ceremony, in 1930, was the first to be broadcast by radio, and the 1953 ceremony was the first to be televised.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It is the oldest of the four major annual American entertainment awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Its counterparts — the Emmy Awards for television, the Tony Awards for Broadway theatre, and the Grammy Awards for music — are modeled after the Academy Awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Oscar statuette depicts a knight, rendered in the Art Deco style.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The first Academy Awards presentation was held on May 16, 1929 at a private dinner function at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel, with an audience of about 270 people.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The post-awards party was held at the Mayfair Hotel.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The cost of guest tickets for that night's ceremony was $5 (equivalent to $94 in 2025).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Fifteen statuettes were awarded, honoring artists, directors, and other participants in the film-making industry of the time, for their works during the 1927–28 period.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For this first ceremony, winners were announced to the media three months earlier.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For the second ceremony in 1930, and the rest of the first decade, the results were given to newspapers for publication at 11:00 pm on the night of the awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1940, the *Los Angeles Times* announced the winners before the ceremony began.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] As a result, in 1941 the Academy started using a sealed envelope to reveal the names of the winners.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The term "Oscar" is a registered trademark of the AMPAS.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Historically, the Oscars had been the prime example of glamor in the United States; however, a movement away from both network television and award shows has led to the shift of the focus of glamor from the Oscars to the Met Gala.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Oscars have suffered declining network television ratings and will be moving to YouTube in 2029.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The first Best Actor awarded was Emil Jannings, for his performances in *The Last Command* and *The Way of All Flesh*.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] As he had to return to Europe before the ceremony, the Academy agreed to give him the prize early, making him the first Academy Award recipient.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For the first Awards, winners were recognized for multiple films during the qualifying period; Jannings received the award for two films in which he starred, and Janet Gaynor won the first Best Actress award for performances in three films.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Beginning with the second ceremony, performers received separate nominations for individual films; no performer has received multiple nominations in the same category since the 3rd Academy Awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For the first five ceremonies, the eligibility period ran from August 1 to July 31.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Best Foreign Language Film, now known as Best International Feature Film, was introduced at the 20th Academy Awards as a special award, and became a competitive category at the 29th Academy Awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 74th Academy Awards, held in 2002, presented the first Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, won by *Shrek*.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Since 1973, all Academy Awards ceremonies, except for 2021, have ended with the Academy Award for Best Picture.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Traditionally, the winners of the acting categories will present an award at the following year's ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The previous year's winners for Best Actor and Best Supporting Actor present the awards for Best Actress and Best Supporting Actress, respectively, and vice versa.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2009, this model was replaced by each acting award being introduced by five previous winners, each of whom introduces one of the nominated performances, referred to as the "Fab 5" presenters format.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Fab 5 model returned in 2024 after a 15-year hiatus.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] On February 9, 2020, *Parasite* became the first foreign-language film to win Best Picture at the 92nd Academy Awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 93rd Academy Awards ceremony, honoring the best films of 2020 and early 2021, was held on April 25, 2021, after it was postponed from its original February 28, 2021, schedule due to the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on cinema.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] As with the two previous ceremonies, there was no host.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It took place at the Dolby Theatre in Los Angeles, California for the 19th consecutive year, with satellite locations at Union Station also in Los Angeles.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Because of the virus impact on films and TV industries, Academy president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson announced that for the 2021 Oscar Ceremony, streaming films with a previously planned theatrical release were eligible.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The theatrical requirement was reinstated starting with the 95th Academy Awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Oscar statuette, officially the Academy Award of Merit, is given to winners of each year's awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Made of gold-plated bronze on a black metal base, it is 13.5 in (34.3 cm) tall, weighs 8.5 lb (3.9 kg) and depicts a knight rendered in Art Deco style holding a sword standing on a reel of film with five spokes.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The five spokes represent the original branches of the Academy: Actors, Writers, Directors, Producers, and Technicians.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Sculptor George Stanley, who also did the Muse Fountain at the Hollywood Bowl, sculpted Cedric Gibbons' design.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The statuettes presented at the initial ceremonies were gold-plated solid bronze.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Within a few years, the bronze was abandoned in favor of Britannia metal, a pewter-like alloy that is then plated in copper, nickel silver, and finally, 24-karat gold.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Due to a metal shortage during World War II, Oscars were made of painted plaster for three years.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Following the war, the Academy invited recipients to redeem the plaster figures for gold-plated metal ones.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The only addition to the Oscar since it was created is a minor streamlining of the base.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The original Oscar mold was cast in 1928 at the C.W.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Shumway & Sons Foundry in Batavia, Illinois, which also contributed to casting the molds for the Vince Lombardi Trophy and Emmy Award statuettes.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] From 1972 to 1986, the Oscar statues were cast at the Dodge Trophy Company in Crystal Lake, Illinois.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] From 1987 to 2015, approximately 50 Oscars in a tin alloy with gold plating were made each year in Chicago by Illinois manufacturer R.S.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It would take between three and four weeks to manufacture 50 statuettes.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2016, the Academy returned to bronze as the core metal of the statuettes, handing manufacturing duties to Walden, New York-based Polich Tallix Fine Art Foundry, now owned and operated by UAP Urban Art Projects.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] While based on a digital scan of an original 1929 Oscar, the statuettes retain their modern-era dimensions and black pedestal.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Cast in liquid bronze from 3D-printed ceramic molds and polished, they are then electroplated in 24-karat gold by Brooklyn, New York-based Epner Technology.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The time required to produce 50 such statuettes is roughly three months.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Owens is expected to continue producing other awards for the Academy, and service existing Oscars that need replating.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The origin of the nickname of the trophy has been disputed, as multiple people have taken credit for naming the trophy "Oscar".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Margaret Herrick, librarian and president of the Academy, may have said she named it after her supposed uncle Oscar in 1931.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The only corroboration was a 1938 clipping from the *Los Angeles Examiner*, in which Herrick told a story of her and her husband joking with each other using the phrase, "How's your uncle Oscar".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Bette Davis, in her 1962 autobiography, claimed she named it in 1936 after her first husband, Harmon Oscar Nelson, of whom the statue's rear end reminded her.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] But the term had been in use at least two years before.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] But in the newspaper clipping that Skolsky referred to, he wrote that "these statues are called 'Oscars'", meaning that the name was already in use.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2021, Brazilian researcher Waldemar Dalenogare Neto contradicted Skolsky's claim to have used the term first, finding the probable first public mention of the name "Oscar" in journalist Relman Morin's "Cinematters" column in the *Los Angeles Evening Record* on December 5, 1933.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Since the awards did not take place that year, he said: "What's happened to the annual Academy banquet?
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Bruce Davis, a former executive director of the Academy, credited Eleanore Lilleberg, a secretary at the Academy when the award was first introduced, for the nickname.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] She had overseen the pre-ceremony handling of the awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Davis credits Lilleberg because he found in an autobiography of Einar Lilleberg, Eleanore's brother, that Einar had referenced a Norwegian army veteran named Oscar whom the two knew in Chicago, whom Einar described as having always "stood straight and tall".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] He asserts credit "should almost certainly belong to" Lilleberg.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] To prevent information identifying the Oscar winners from leaking ahead of the ceremony, Oscar statuettes presented at the ceremony have blank baseplates.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Until 2010, winners returned their statuettes to the Academy and had to wait several weeks to have their names inscribed on their respective Oscars.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Since 2010, winners have had the option of having engraved nameplates applied to their statuettes at an inscription-processing station at the Governor's Ball, a party held immediately after the Oscar ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Owens company has engraved nameplates made before the ceremony, bearing the name of every potential winner.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The nameplates for the non-winning nominees are later recycled.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Before 1950, Oscar statuettes were, and remain, the property of the recipient.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Since then the statuettes have been legally encumbered by the requirement that the statuette be first offered for sale back to the Academy for $1.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] If a winner refuses to agree to this stipulation, then the Academy keeps the statuette.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Academy Awards predating this agreement have been sold in public auctions and private deals for six-figure sums.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1989, Michael Todd's grandson tried to sell Todd's Best Picture Oscar for his 1956 production of *Around the World in 80 Days* to a movie prop collector.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy earned enforcement of its statuette contract by gaining a permanent injunction against the sale.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1992, Harold Russell consigned his 1946 Oscar for Best Supporting Actor for *The Best Years of Our Lives* to auction to raise money for his wife's medical expenses.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Though his decision caused controversy, the first Oscar ever to be sold passed to a private collector on August 6, 1992, for $60,500 (equivalent to $138,804 in 2025).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Russell defended his action, saying, "I don't know why anybody would be critical.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] My wife's health is much more important than sentimental reasons.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The movie will be here, even if Oscar isn't".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In December 2011, Orson Welles' 1941 Oscar for *Citizen Kane* (Academy Award for Best Original Screenplay) was put up for auction, after his heirs won a 2004 court decision contending that Welles did not sign any agreement to return the statue to the Academy.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Some buyers have subsequently returned the statuettes to the Academy, which keeps them in its treasury.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy also awards Nicholl Fellowships in Screenwriting.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] From 2004 to 2020, the Academy Award nomination results were announced to the public in mid-January.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Prior to that, the results were announced in early February.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2021, the nominees were announced in March.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2022, the nominees were announced in early February for the first time since 2003.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), a professional honorary organization, is composed of 9,905 voting members as of 2024.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Academy membership is divided into different branches, with each representing a different discipline in film production.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] As of 2024, actors constitute the largest bloc, numbering 1,258 (12.7% of the voting body).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Votes have been certified by the auditing firm PricewaterhouseCoopers, and its predecessor Price Waterhouse, since the 7th Academy Awards in 1935.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In May 2011, the Academy sent a letter advising its then-6,000 or so voting members that an online system for Oscar voting would be implemented in 2013, replacing mailed paper ballots.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] All AMPAS members must be invited to join by the Board of Governors, on behalf of Academy Branch Executive Committees.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Membership eligibility may be achieved by a competitive nomination, or an existing member may submit a name, based on other significant contributions to the field of motion pictures.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] New membership proposals are considered annually.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy does not publicly disclose its membership, although as recently as 2007 press releases have announced the names of those who have been invited to join.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2012, the results of a study conducted by the *Los Angeles Times* were published describing the demographic breakdown of approximately 88% of AMPAS' voting membership.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Of the 5,100+ active voters confirmed, 94% were Caucasian, 77% were male, and 54% were found to be over the age of 60.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Thirty-three percent of voting members are former nominees (14%) and winners (19%).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2016, the Academy launched an initiative to expand its membership and increase diversity.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2024, voting membership stood at 9,905.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2025, a newly announced procedure required Academy members to view all nominated films within a category to be eligible to cast a vote in the final round of that category.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The verification process will be done through the Academy's members-only streaming platform and submitting a form for films viewed at in-person events such as at festivals, screenings or private events.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The film must be shown at least three times on each day of its qualifying run, with at least one of the daily showings starting between 6 pm and 10 pm local time.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For example, the 2009 Best Picture winner, *The Hurt Locker*, was originally first released in 2008, but did not qualify for the 2008 awards, as it did not play its Oscar-qualifying run in Los Angeles until mid-2009, thus qualifying for the 2009 awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Foreign films must include English subtitles.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Each country can submit only one film for consideration in the International Feature Film category per year.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Rule 2 states that a film must be feature-length, defined as a minimum of 40 minutes, except for short-subject awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It must exist either on a 35 mm or 70 mm film print, or in 24 frame/s or 48 frame/s progressive scan digital cinema format, with a minimum projector resolution of 2,048 by 1,080 pixels.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Since the 90th Academy Awards, presented in 2018, multi-part and limited series have been ineligible for the Best Documentary Feature award.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] This followed the win of *O.J.: Made in America*, an eight-hour presentation that was screened in a limited release before being broadcast in five parts on ABC and ESPN, in that category in 2017.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy's announcement of the new rule made no direct mention of that film.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Best International Feature Film award does not require a U.S. release.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It requires the film to be submitted as its country's official selection.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The qualifying theatrical runs must meet the same requirements as those for non-documentary films regarding numbers and times of screenings.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] A film must have been reviewed by a critic from *The New York Times*, *Time Out New York*, the *Los Angeles Times*, or *LA Weekly*.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Producers must submit an Official Screen Credits online form before the deadline.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] If it is not submitted by the defined deadline, the film will be ineligible for Academy Awards in any year.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The form includes the production credits for all related categories.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Awards in short film categories (Best Documentary Short Subject, Best Animated Short Film, and Best Live Action Short Film) have different eligibility rules from most other competitive awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] First, the qualifying period for release does not coincide with a calendar year, instead covering one year starting on October 1, and ending on September 30 of the calendar year before the ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Second, there are multiple methods of qualification.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The main method is a week-long theatrical release in *either* New York City *or* Los Angeles County during the eligibility period.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Films can also qualify by winning specified awards at one of several competitive film festivals designated by the Academy, also without regard to prior public distribution.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] A film that is selected as a gold, silver, or bronze medal winner in an appropriate category of the immediately previous Student Academy Awards is also eligible (Documentary category for that award, and Animation, Narrative, Alternative, or International for the other awards).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The requirements for the qualifying theatrical run are also different from those for other awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For the Documentary award, the screening must start between noon and 10 pm local time.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For other awards, no specific start time is required, but the film must appear in regular theater listings with dates and screening times.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In late December, ballots and lists of eligible films are sent to the membership.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For most categories, members from each of the branches vote to determine the nominees only in their respective categories, i.e. only directors vote for directors, writers for writers, actors for actors, etc.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In the special case of Best Picture, all voting members are eligible to select the nominees.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] A number of branches are only eligible to vote in Best Picture during nomination voting; this includes a producers' branch, as Best Picture is awarded to a film's producer(s), and other branches which have no corresponding award.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In all major categories, a variant of the single transferable vote is used, with each member casting a ballot with up to five nominees (ten for Best Picture) ranked preferentially.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In certain categories, including International Feature Film, Documentary and Animated Feature, nominees are selected by special screening committees made up of members from all branches.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In most categories, the winner is selected from among the nominees by plurality voting of all members.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Since 2009, the Best Picture winner has been chosen by instant-runoff voting.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Since 2013, re-weighted range voting has been used to select the nominees for the Best Visual Effects.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Film companies will spend as much as several million dollars on marketing to awards voters for a film in the running for Best Picture, in attempts to improve chances of receiving Oscars and other film awards conferred in Oscar season.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy enforces rules to limit overt campaigning by its members to try to eliminate excesses and prevent the process from becoming undignified.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It has an awards czar on staff who advises members on allowed practices and levies penalties on offenders.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For example, a producer of the 2009 Best Picture nominee *The Hurt Locker* was disqualified as a producer in the category when he contacted associates urging them to vote for his film and not another that was seen as the front-runner.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For the 99th Academy Awards (2027) and thereafter, AMPAS announced on May 1, 2026, its planned rules of eligibility.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Actors and scripts generated by artificial intelligence (AI) will be excluded from acting and screenwriting categories, but human actors rendered by AI will be reviewed at discretion.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Another rule change will expand eligibility of international films by allowing films that won eligible qualifying awards at film festivals, like the Palme d'Or (Cannes), the Golden Lion (Venice), and the Platform Prize (Toronto).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Another new rule will allow an actor to be nominated more than once in a same acting category of the year.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Another rule change will clarify eligibility of the Best Original Song category: to be eligible, a first song played as the "first music cue" of the end credits must be heard in at least the film's last fifteen seconds until the end credits start.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy Screening Room or Academy Digital Screening Room is a secure streaming platform which allows voting members of the Academy to view all eligible films in one place.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It was introduced in 2019, for the 2020 Oscars.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] DVD screeners and Academy in-person screenings were still provided.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For films to be included on the platform, the North American distributor must pay $12,500, including a watermarking fee, and a digital copy of the film to be prepared for streaming by the Academy.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The platform can be accessed via Apple TV and Roku players.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The watermarking process involved several video security firms, creating a forensic watermark and restricting the ability to take screenshots or screen recordings.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2021, for the 2022 Oscars, the Academy banned all physical screeners and in-person screenings, restricting official membership viewing to the Academy Screening Room.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Films eligible in the Documentary and International categories were made available in different sections of the platform.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Distributors can also pay an extra fee to add video featurettes to promote their films on the platform.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The in-person screenings were cancelled because of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Eligible films do not have to be added to the platform, but the Academy advertises them to voting members when they are.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The major awards are presented at a live televised ceremony, commonly in late February or early March following the relevant calendar year, and six weeks after the announcement of the nominees.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] It is the culmination of the film awards season, which usually begins during November or December of the previous year.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] This is an elaborate extravaganza, with the invited guests walking up the red carpet in the creations of the most prominent fashion designers of the day.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Black tie dress is the most common outfit for men.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Fashion may dictate not wearing a bow tie, and musical performers are sometimes not required to adhere to this.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The artists who recorded the nominees for Best Original Song quite often perform those songs live at the awards ceremony, and the fact that they are performing is often used to promote the television broadcast.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy Awards is the world's longest-running awards show televised live from the United States to all time zones in North America and worldwide, and gathers millions of viewers elsewhere throughout the world.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Oscars were first televised in 1953 by NBC, which continued to broadcast the event until 1960, when ABC took over, televising the festivities, including the first color broadcast of the event in 1966, to 1970.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] NBC regained the rights for five years (1971–75), then ABC resumed broadcast duties in 1976 and its current contract with the Academy runs through 2028, after which the ceremony will be broadcast exclusively on YouTube starting with 2029's ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy has produced condensed versions of the ceremony for broadcast in international markets, especially those outside of the Americas, in more desirable local timeslots.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The ceremony was broadcast live internationally for the first time via satellite since 1970, but only two South American countries, Chile and Brazil, purchased the rights to air the broadcast.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] By that time, the television rights to the Academy Awards had been sold in 50 countries.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1980, the rights were sold to 60 countries, and by 1984, the television rights to the Academy Awards were licensed in 76 countries.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2004, the ceremonies were moved up from late March/early April to late February, to help disrupt and shorten the intense lobbying and ad campaigns associated with Oscar season in the film industry.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Another reason was because of the growing television ratings success coinciding with the NCAA division I men's basketball tournament, which would cut into the Academy Awards audience.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1976 and 1977, ABC's regained Oscars were moved from Tuesday to Monday and went directly opposite the national championship game on NBC.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The earlier date is also to the advantage of ABC, as it now usually occurs during the highly profitable and important February sweeps period.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Some years, the ceremony is moved into the first Sunday of March to avoid a clash with the Winter Olympics.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Another reason for the move to late February and early March is to avoid the awards ceremony occurring so close to the religious holidays of Passover and Easter, which for decades had been a grievance from members and the general public.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Advertising is somewhat restricted, as traditionally no film studios or competitors of official Academy Award sponsors may advertise during the telecast.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] As of 2020, the production of the Academy Awards telecast held the distinction of winning one the highest number of Emmys in history, with 54 wins and 280 nominations overall.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] After many years of being held on Mondays at 6:00 p.m.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Eastern, since the 1999 ceremony, it was moved to Sundays at 5:30 p.m.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The reasons given for the move were that more viewers would tune in on Sundays, that Los Angeles rush-hour traffic jams could be avoided, and an earlier start time would prevent the ceremony from going late into the night in the East.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] For many years the film industry opposed a Sunday broadcast because it would cut into the weekend box office.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2010, the Academy contemplated moving the ceremony even further back into January, citing television viewers' fatigue with the film industry's long awards season.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] However, such an accelerated schedule would dramatically decrease the voting period for its members, to the point where some voters would only have time to view the contending films streamed on their computers, as opposed to traditionally receiving the films and ballots in the mail.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Additionally, a January ceremony on Sunday would clash with National Football League (NFL) playoff games.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2018, the Academy announced that the ceremony would be moved from late February to mid-February beginning with the 92nd Academy Awards in 2020.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2024, the ceremony was moved to an even earlier start time of 4:00 p.m.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] ET, in an effort to improve East Coast viewership by having it conclude within primetime hours.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The change also gave the ability for ABC to air a half-hour of primetime programming as a lead-out program at 7:30 p.m.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] ET, after having sometimes done so in the late-night block following late local newscasts.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Originally scheduled for April 8, 1968, the 40th Academy Awards ceremony was postponed for two days, because of the assassination of Dr.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] On March 30, 1981, the 53rd Academy Awards was postponed for one day, after the attempted assassination of President Ronald Reagan and others in Washington, D.C.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1993, an *In Memoriam* segment was introduced, honoring those who had made a significant contribution to cinema who had died in the preceding 12 months, a selection compiled by a small committee of Academy members.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] This segment has drawn criticism over the years for the omission of some names.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Criticism was also levied for many years regarding another aspect, with the segment having a "popularity contest" feel as the audience varied their applause to those who had died by the subject's cultural impact.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The applause has since been muted during the telecast, and the audience is discouraged from clapping during the segment and giving silent reflection instead.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] This segment was later followed by a commercial break.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In terms of broadcast length, the ceremony generally averages three and a half hours.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The first Oscars, in 1929, lasted 15 minutes.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] At the other end of the spectrum, the 2002 ceremony lasted four hours and twenty-three minutes.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2010, the organizers of the Academy Awards announced winners' acceptance speeches must not run past 45 seconds.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] This, according to organizer Bill Mechanic, was to ensure the elimination of what he termed "the single most hated thing on the show"—overly long and embarrassing displays of emotion.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2016, in a further effort to streamline speeches, winners' dedications were displayed on an on-screen ticker.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] During the 2018 ceremony, host Jimmy Kimmel acknowledged how long the ceremony had become, by announcing that he would give a brand-new jet ski to whoever gave the shortest speech of the night, a reward won by Mark Bridges when accepting his Best Costume Design award for *Phantom Thread*.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Although still dominant in ratings, the viewership of the Academy Awards has steadily dropped.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 88th Academy Awards were the lowest-rated in the past eight years (although with increases in male and 18–49 viewership), while the show itself also faced mixed reception.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Following the show, *Variety* reported that ABC was, in negotiating an extension to its contract to broadcast the Oscars, seeking to have more creative control over the broadcast itself.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Currently and nominally, AMPAS is responsible for most aspects of the telecast, including the choice of production staff and hosting, although ABC is allowed to have some input on their decisions.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In August 2016, AMPAS extended its contract with ABC to 2028: the contract neither contains any notable changes nor gives ABC any further creative control over the telecast.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] On December 17, 2025, the Academy announced that YouTube had acquired the rights to the Academy Awards beginning with the 101st ceremony in 2029, replacing ABC under a contract that will last through 2033.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] YouTube will serve as the exclusive worldwide broadcaster of the ceremony, while the Oscars' YouTube channel will also feature other AMPAS-produced ancillary content and events (including ceremonies, interviews, and other digital content).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy will also partner with the Google Arts & Culture program to help digitize portions of the Academy Museum of Motion Pictures and the organization's collection.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Historically, the telecast's viewership is higher when box-office hits are favored to win the Best Picture award.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] More than 57.25 million viewers tuned to the telecast for the 70th Academy Awards in 1998, the year of *Titanic*, which generated a box office haul during its initial 1997–98 run of $600.8 million in the US, a box-office record that would remain unsurpassed for years.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 76th Academy Awards ceremony, in which *The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King* (pre-telecast box office earnings of $368 million) received 11 Awards, including Best Picture, drew 43.56 million viewers.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The most-watched ceremony based on Nielsen ratings to date, was the 42nd Academy Awards (Best Picture *Midnight Cowboy*), which drew a 43.4% household rating on April 7, 1970.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Hoping to reinvigorate the pre-show and ratings, the 2023 Oscars organizers hired members of the Met Gala creative team.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] By contrast, ceremonies honoring films that have not performed well at the box office tend to show weaker ratings, despite how much critical acclaim those films have received.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 78th Academy Awards, which awarded a low-budget independent film (*Crash* with a pre-Oscar gross of $53.4 million) generated an audience of 38.64 million with a household rating of 22.91%.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2008, the 80th Academy Awards telecast was watched by 31.76 million viewers on average with an 18.66% household rating, the lowest-rated and least-watched ceremony at the time, in spite of celebrating 80 years of the Academy Awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Best Picture winner of that particular ceremony was another independent film (this time, the Coen brothers's *No Country for Old Men*).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Whereas the 92nd Academy Awards drew an average of 23.6 million viewers, the 93rd Academy Awards drew an even lower viewership of 10.4 million, the lowest viewership recorded by Nielsen since it started recording audience totals in 1974.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 94th and 95th editions drew 16.6 and 18.7 million viewers, respectively, still below the audience of the 92nd edition.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Academy Film Archive holds copies of every Academy Awards ceremony since the 1949 Oscars, as well as material on many prior ceremonies, along with ancillary material related to more recent shows.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Copies are held in a variety of film, video and digital formats.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1929, the first Academy Awards were presented at a banquet dinner at the Hollywood Roosevelt Hotel.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] From 1930 to 1943, the ceremony alternated between two venues: the Ambassador Hotel on Wilshire Boulevard and the Biltmore Hotel in downtown Los Angeles.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Grauman's Chinese Theatre in Hollywood then hosted the awards from 1944 to 1946, followed by the Shrine Auditorium in Los Angeles from 1947 to 1948.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The 21st Academy Awards in 1949 were held at the Academy Award Theatre at what had been the Academy's headquarters on Melrose Avenue in Hollywood.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] From 1950 to 1960, the awards were presented at Hollywood's Pantages Theatre.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] With the advent of television, the awards from 1953 to 1957 took place simultaneously in Hollywood and New York, first at the NBC International Theatre (1953) and the Center Theater (1954), then at the NBC Century Theatre, after which the ceremony took place solely in Los Angeles.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1961, the Oscars moved to the Santa Monica Civic Auditorium in Santa Monica, California.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 1969, the Academy moved the ceremonies back to Downtown Los Angeles, to the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion at the Los Angeles County Music Center.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the ceremony returned to the Shrine Auditorium.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In 2002, Hollywood's Dolby Theatre, previously known as the Kodak Theatre, became the presentation's current venue.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In March 2026, it was announced that the ceremony would relocate to the Peacock Theater beginning in 2029, under a ten-year deal with the venue.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In the first year of the awards, the Best Directing award was split into two categories, Drama and Comedy.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] At times, the Best Original Score award has also been split into separate categories, Drama and Comedy/Musical.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] From the 1930s to the 1960s, the Art Direction (now Production Design), Cinematography, and Costume Design awards were split into two categories (black-and-white films and color films).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Prior to 2012, the Production Design award was called Art Direction, while the Makeup and Hairstyling award was called Makeup.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Prior to 2020, the International Feature Film award was called Foreign Language Film.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In August 2018, the Academy announced that several categories would not be televised live, but recorded during commercial breaks and aired later in the ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] Following dissent from Academy members, they announced that they would air all 24 categories live.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] This followed several proposals, among them, the introduction of a Popular Film category, that the Academy had announced but did not implement.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In February 2024, the Academy announced it would introduce an award for Achievement in Casting from the 98th ceremony in 2026, having rejected the category in 1999.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] In April 2025, it announced that Best Stunt Design would be introduced from the 100th ceremony in 2028, having rejected the proposal for a Best Stunt Coordination award every year from 1991 to 2012.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] The Special Academy Awards are voted on by special committees, rather than by the Academy membership as a whole.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p01] They are not always presented on an annual basis.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Due to the positive exposure and prestige of the Academy Awards, many studios spend around 25 million dollars and hire publicists specifically to promote their films during what is typically called the "Oscar season".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] This has generated accusations of the Academy Awards being influenced more by marketing and lobbying than by quality.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] William Friedkin, an Academy Award-winning film director and former producer of the ceremony, expressed this sentiment at a conference in New York in 2009, describing it as "the greatest promotion scheme that any industry ever devised for itself".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] A recent technique that has been claimed to be used during the Oscar season is the whisper campaign.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] These campaigns are intended to spread negative perceptions of other films nominated and are believed to be perpetrated by those who were involved in creating the film.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Examples of whisper campaigns include the allegations against *Zero Dark Thirty* suggesting that it justifies torture and the claim that *Lincoln* distorts history.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] This technique was widely used by former producer Harvey Weinstein and his company Miramax, with the campaign strategy gaining further attention after Miramax's *Shakespeare in Love* defeated rival film *Saving Private Ryan* for Best Picture.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The Oscars have been infamously known for selecting specific genres of films to be awarded.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The term "Oscar bait" was coined to describe such films.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] This has led, at times, to more specific criticisms that the Academy is disconnected from the audience, e.g., by favoring "Oscar bait" over audience favorites or favoring historical melodramas over critically acclaimed films that depict current life issues.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Despite the success of *The Dark Knight* and *WALL-E*, these films did not receive a Best Picture nomination at the 81st Academy Awards.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] These decisions received substantial criticism and were described as "snubs" by many publications.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The backlash to the decision was such that, for the 82nd Academy Awards in 2010, the Academy increased the limit for Best Picture nominees from five to ten.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The Academy Awards have long received criticism over their lack of diversity among the nominees.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] This criticism is based on the statistics from every Academy Awards since 1929, which show that only 6.4% of Academy Award nominees have been non-white and since 1991, 11.2% of nominees have been non-white, with the rate of winners being even more polarizing.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] For a variety of reasons, including marketability and historical bans on interracial couples, a number of high-profile Oscars have been given to yellowface portrayals, as well as performances of Asian characters rewritten for white characters.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] It took until 2023 for an Asian woman to win an Academy Award for Best Actress, when Michelle Yeoh received the award for her performance in *Everything Everywhere All at Once*.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The 88th awards ceremony became the target of a boycott, popularized on social media with the hashtag #OscarsSoWhite, based on activists' perception that its all-white acting nominee list reflected bias.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] In response, the Academy initiated "historic" changes in membership by 2020.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Some media critics claim the Academy's efforts to address its purported racial, gender and national biases are merely distractions.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] By contrast, the Golden Globe Awards already have multiple winners of Asian descent in leading actress categories.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Some question whether the Academy's definition of "merit" is just or empowering for non-Americans.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The Academy's Representation and Inclusion Standards have been criticized for excluding Jews as a distinct underrepresented class.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The Academy has no rules for how to categorize whether a performance is leading or supporting, and it is up to the discretion of the studios whether a given performance is submitted for either Best Actor/Actress or Best Supporting Actor/Actress.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] This has led to situations where a film has two or more co-leads, and one of these is submitted in a supporting category to avoid the two leads competing against each other, and to increase the film's chances of winning.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] This practice has been derisively called "category fraud".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] For example, Rooney Mara was nominated for Best Supporting Actress for *Carol* (2015), despite her having a comparable amount of screentime to Cate Blanchett, who was nominated for Best Actress.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Another example is *Once Upon a Time in Hollywood* (2019), where Brad Pitt was nominated for and won Best Supporting Actor, even though he played an equally important role to Best Actor nominee Leonardo DiCaprio.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] In both these cases, critics argued that the studios behind the films had placed someone who was actually a leading actor or actress into the supporting categories to avoid them competing against their co-lead.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Following its April 2019 board meeting, the Academy Board of Governors agreed to retain the current rules that allow for streaming media films to be eligible for Oscars as long as they have had limited theatrical runs.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] During the 94th Academy Awards on March 27, 2022, Chris Rock joked about Jada Pinkett Smith's shaved head with a *G.I.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Will Smith walked onstage and slapped Rock across the face, then returned to his seat and told Rock, twice, to "Keep my wife's name out [of] your fucking mouth!" While later accepting the Best Actor award for *King Richard*, Smith apologized to the Academy and the other nominees, but not to Rock.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Rock decided not to press charges against Smith.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] On April 8, 2022, the Academy made an announcement via a letter sent by president David Rubin and CEO Dawn Hudson informing the public that Will Smith had received a ten-year ban from attending the Oscars as a result of the incident.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Some winners critical of the Academy Awards have boycotted the ceremonies and refused to accept their Oscars.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The first to do so was screenwriter Dudley Nichols (Best Writing in 1935 for *The Informer*).
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Nichols boycotted the 8th Academy Awards ceremony because of conflicts between the Academy and the Writers' Guild.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Nichols eventually accepted the 1935 award three years later, at the 1938 ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Nichols was nominated for three further Academy Awards during his career.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Scott became the second person to refuse his award (Best Actor in 1970 for *Patton*) at the 43rd Academy Awards ceremony.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Scott described it as a "meat parade", saying, "I don't want any part of it".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The third person to refuse the award was Marlon Brando, who refused his award (Best Actor for 1972's *The Godfather*), citing the film industry's discrimination against and mistreatment of Native Americans.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] At the 45th Academy Awards ceremony, Brando asked actress and civil rights activist Sacheen Littlefeather to read a 15-page speech in his place, detailing his criticisms, for which there was booing and cheering by the audience.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] In 2022, Littlefeather was accused by her sisters of misrepresenting her ancestry as Native American.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Adding to the controversy was that the award for Best Animated Short Film (the nominees for which were mostly made up of shorts not aimed at children) was one of the eight categories that were not presented during the live broadcast.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Alberto Mielgo, director of *The Windshield Wiper*, later gave an acceptance speech for the Oscar: "Animation is an art that includes every single art that you can imagine.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] I'm very honored because this is just the beginning of what we can do with animation." Some speculations suggested that the speech played a role in the decision not to broadcast the award.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The PG-13-rated *The Boy and the Heron* would subsequently win the award.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] It has become a tradition to give out gift bags to the presenters and performers at the Oscars.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] In recent years, these gifts have been extended to award nominees and winners.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The value of each of these gift bags can reach into the tens of thousands of dollars.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] In 2014, the value was reported to be as high as $80,000.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] The value has risen to the point where the U.S.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Internal Revenue Service issued a statement regarding the gifts and their taxable status.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Some of the gifts have even had a "risque" element to them; in 2014, the adult products retailer Adam & Eve had a "Secret Room Gifting Suite".
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] Celebrities visiting the gifting suite included Judith Hoag, Carolyn Hennesy, Kate Linder, Chris Mulkey, Jim O'Heir and John Salley.
[src:amherst-college/academy-awards-p02] From 2006 onwards, results are Live+SD; all previous years are live viewing.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The **ACT** (/ˈeɪ.ˌsiː.ˌtiː/ ⓘ, *AY-see-tee*; originally an abbreviation of **American College Testing**) is a standardized test used for college admissions in the United States.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] It is administered by ACT, Inc., a for-profit organization of the same name.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT test covers three academic skill areas: English, mathematics, and reading.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] It also offers optional scientific reasoning and direct writing tests.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] It is accepted by many four-year colleges and universities in the United States as well as more than 225 universities outside of the U.S.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The multiple-choice test sections of the ACT (all except the optional writing test) are individually scored on a scale of 1–36.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] In addition, a composite score consisting of the rounded whole number average of the scores for English, reading, and math is provided.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT was first introduced in November 1959 by University of Iowa professor Everett Franklin Lindquist as a competitor to the SAT.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT originally consisted of four tests: English, Mathematics, Social Studies, and Natural Sciences.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] In 1989, however, the Social Studies test was changed into a Reading section (which included a social sciences subsection), and the Natural Sciences test was renamed the Science Reasoning test, with more emphasis on problem-solving skills as opposed to memorizing scientific facts.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] In February 2005, an optional Writing Test was added to the ACT.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] By the fall of 2017, computer-based ACT tests were available for school-day testing in limited school districts of the US, with greater availability expected in fall of 2018.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] In July 2024, the ACT announced that the test duration was shortened; the science section, like the writing one, would become optional; and online testing would be rolled out nationally in spring 2025 and for school-day testing in spring 2026.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT has seen a gradual increase in the number of test takers since its inception, and in 2012 the ACT surpassed the SAT for the first time in total test takers; that year, 1,666,017 students took the ACT and 1,664,479 students took the SAT.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] On June 30th, 2026, ETS, the largest educational testing and assessment nonprofit, announced the acquisition of ACT.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] ACT, Inc., says that the ACT assessment measures high school students' general educational development and their capability to complete college-level work with the multiple choice tests covering four skill areas: English, mathematics, reading, and (optionally) science.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The optional Writing Test measures skill in planning and writing a short essay.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Specifically, ACT states that its scores provide an indicator of "college readiness", and that scores in each of the subtests correspond to skills in entry-level college courses in English, algebra, social science, humanities, and biology.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] According to a research study conducted by ACT, Inc. in 2003, there was a relationship between a student's ACT composite score and the probability of that student earning a college degree.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] To develop the test, ACT incorporates the objectives for instruction from middle and high schools throughout the United States, reviews approved textbooks for subjects taught in Grades 7–12, and surveys educators on which knowledge skills are relevant to success in postsecondary education.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] ACT publishes a technical manual that summarizes studies conducted on its validity in predicting freshman GPA, equating different high school GPAs, and measuring educational achievement.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] ACT scores are used to supplement the secondary school record and help admission officers put local data—such as coursework, grades, and class rank—in a national perspective.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The majority of colleges do not indicate a preference for the SAT or ACT exams and accept both, being treated equally by most admissions officers.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Most colleges use ACT scores as only one factor in the admission process.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] A sampling of ACT admissions scores shows that the 75th percentile composite score was 24.1 at public four-year institutions and 25.3 at private four-year institutions.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] In addition, some states and individual school districts have used the ACT to assess student learning and/or the performance of schools, requiring all high school students to take the ACT, regardless of whether they are college bound.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Colorado and Illinois were the first to incorporate the ACT as part of their mandatory testing program in 2001.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Other states followed suit in subsequent years.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] During the 2018–2019 school year, 13 states will administer the ACT test to all public school 11th graders, and another six states will fund ACT test administration as an option or choice for districts.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT is more widely used in the Midwestern, Rocky Mountain, and Southern United States, whereas the SAT is more popular on the East and West coasts.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Recently, however, the ACT is being used more on the East Coast.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Use of the ACT by colleges has risen as a result of various criticisms of the effectiveness and fairness of the SAT.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The required portion of the ACT is divided into three multiple-choice subject tests: English, mathematics, and reading.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Subject test scores, including the optional science section, range from 1 to 36; all scores are integers.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The English, mathematics, and reading tests also have subscores ranging from 1 to 18 (the subject score is not the sum of the subscores).
[src:amherst-college/act-test] In addition, students taking the optional writing test receive a writing score ranging from 2 to 12 (this is a change from the previous 1–36 score range); the optional science and writing scores do not affect the composite score.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Prior to September 2015, there was a Combined English/Writing score, which was a 36-point combination of the 36-point English Test score and the 12-point Writing subscore.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT has eliminated the Combined English/writing score and has added two new combined scores: ELA (an average of the English, Reading, and Writing scores) and STEM (an average of the Math and Science scores).
[src:amherst-college/act-test] These changes for the writing, ELA, and STEM scores were effective starting with the September 2015 test.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Each question answered correctly is worth one raw point, and there is no penalty for marking incorrect answers on the multiple-choice parts of the test; a student can answer all questions without a decrease in their score due to incorrect answers.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] This is parallel to several AP Tests eliminating the penalties for incorrect answers.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] To improve the result, students can retake the test: 55% of students who retake the ACT improve their scores, 22% score the same, and 23% see their scores decrease.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The first section is the 45-minute English test covering usage/mechanics, sentence structure, and rhetorical skills.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The 75-question test consists of five passages with various sections underlined on one side of the page and options to correct the underlined portions on the other side of the page.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The second section is a 60-minute, 60-question math test with the usual distribution of questions being approximately 14 covering pre-algebra, 10 elementary algebra, 9 intermediate algebra, 14 plane geometry, 9 coordinate geometry, and 4 elementary trigonometry questions.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] However, the distribution of question topics varies from test to test.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The difficulty of questions usually increases as a test taker moves on to higher question numbers.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Calculators are permitted in this section only.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Standard graphing calculators, such as the TI-83 and TI-84, are allowed.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Within the TI-Nspire family, the standard and CX versions are allowed while the CX CAS is not.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] As of April 2025 for online tests, and September 2025 for paper-and-pencil tests, each math question has four answer choices instead of five.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The reading section is a 35-minute, 40-question test that consists of four sections, three of which contain one long prose passage and one which contains two shorter prose passages.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The passages are representative of the levels and kinds of text commonly encountered in first-year college curriculum.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] This reading test assesses skills in three general categories: key ideas and details, craft and structure, and integration of knowledge and ideas.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Test questions will usually ask students to derive meaning from texts referring to what is explicitly stated or by reasoning to determine implicit meanings.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The optional science section is a 35-minute, 40-question test.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] There are seven passages each followed by five to seven questions.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The passages have three different formats: Data Representation, Research Summary, and Conflicting Viewpoints.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] But so far, there is still always only one Conflicting Viewpoints passage.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] These changes are very recent, and the only reference to them so far is in the recently released practice test on the ACT website.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The science section was mandatory until 2024, when it was made optional with the goal of giving students additional flexibility when taking the ACT exam.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The optional writing section, which is always administered at the end of the test, is 40 minutes (increasing from the original 30-minute time limit on the September 2015 test).
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The essay does not affect the composite score or the English section score; it is only given as a separate writing score and is included in the ELA score.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Two trained readers assign each essay subscores between 1 and 6 in four different categories: Ideas and Analysis, Development and Support, Organization, Language Use and Conventions.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Scores of 0 are reserved for essays that are blank, off-topic, non-English, not written with a no.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] 2 pencil, or considered illegible after several attempts at reading.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The subscores from the two different readers are summed to produce final domain scores from 2 to 12 (or 0) in each of the four categories.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] If the two readers' subscores differ by more than one point, then a senior third reader makes the final decision on the score.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The four domain scores are combined through a process that has not been described to create a writing section score between 1 and 36.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Note that the domain scores are not added to create the writing section score.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Although the writing section is optional, many colleges require an essay score and will factor it into the admissions decision (but fewer than half of all colleges have this requirement).
[src:amherst-college/act-test] For the "enhanced" version of the ACT introduced in 1989, the mean score of each of the four tests, as well as the mean composite score, was scaled to be 18, with an intended standard error of measurement of 2 for the four test scores and 1 for the composite score.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] These statistics vary from year to year for current populations of ACT takers.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The chart below summarizes each section and the average test score based on graduating high school seniors in 2025.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The table below summarizes how many students achieved a composite score of 36 on the ACT between the years of 1990 and 2025.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT Assessment Student Report, at ACT.org, provides the typical ACT Composite averages for college and universities admission policies.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] They caution that "because admission policies vary across colleges, the score ranges should be considered rough guidelines." Following is a list of the average composite scores that typically are accepted at colleges or universities.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT is offered seven times a year in the United States and its territories, Puerto Rico, and Canada: in September, October, December, February, April, June, and July.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] (In New York State, the test is not offered in July.) In other locations, the ACT is offered five times a year: in September, October, December, April, and June.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT is offered only on Saturdays except for those with credible religious obligations, who may take the test on another day.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT is designed, administered, and scored so that there is no advantage to testing on one particular date.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] For candidates in the United States, the ACT assessment costs $65.00 and there are two optional add-ons, the science section ($4.00) and the writing section ($25.00).
[src:amherst-college/act-test] For candidates outside of the United States, the test costs considerably more, at $186.50, with science costing $10.00, although writing retains its price of $25.00.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] For the 2025 testing dates, the science section is only optional for the digital test.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Students with verifiable disabilities, including physical and learning disabilities, are eligible to take the test with accommodations.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The standard time increase for students requiring additional time due to disabilities is 50%.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Originally, the score sheet was labeled that additional time was granted due to a learning disability; however, this was ultimately dropped because it was deemed illegal under the Americans with Disabilities Act and could be perceived as an unfair designator of disability.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Scores are sent to the student, their high school, and up to four colleges of the student's choice (optional).
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Time is a major factor to consider in testing.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The ACT is generally regarded as being composed of somewhat easier questions versus the SAT, but the shorter time allotted to complete each section increases difficulty.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Comparatively, the SAT is structured such that the test taker is allowed at least one minute per question, on generally shorter sections (25 or fewer questions).
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Times may be adjusted as a matter of accommodation for certain disabilities or other impairments.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Score reports provided to students taking the ACT test include the ranks (or cumulative percents) for each score and subscore received by the student.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Each rank gives the percentage of recently tested students in the U.S. who scored at or below the given student's score.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The following table shows the ACT national ranks as of the 2020-21 school year.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The College Board (the developer of the SAT) and ACT, Inc. compared scores from about 600,000 students who were graduating in 2017 and who took both the SAT (2016 revision) and the ACT in 2016 and 2017.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The following table shows, for each ACT composite score in the data set, the corresponding range of SAT total scores for students with the same percentile rank on each test.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The most appropriate corresponding SAT score point for the given ACT score is also shown in the table.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The data in this section pertains to the SAT prior to the 2016 redesign.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Comparisons to SAT scores are not valid after the 2017 graduating class.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Sixty percent—about 2.03 million students—of the 2017 high school graduating class took the ACT.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] For the graduating class of 2017, the average composite score was a 21.0.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] Of these test-takers, 46% were male and 52% were female, with 2% not reporting a gender.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] 2,760 students in the graduating class of 2017 received the highest ACT composite score of 36.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] The following chart shows, for each ACT score from 11 to 36, the corresponding ACT percentile and equivalent total SAT score or score range.
[src:amherst-college/act-test] (Concordance data for ACT scores less than 11 is not yet available for the current version of the SAT.) Note that ACT percentiles are defined as the percentage of test takers scoring at or below the given score.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The college was founded in 1889 as **Decatur Female Seminary** by Presbyterian minister Frank Henry Gaines.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] In 1890, the name was changed to **Agnes Scott Institute** to honor the mother of the college's primary benefactor, Col.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The name was changed again to Agnes Scott College in 1906 and remains today a women's college.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is considered the first higher education institution in the state of Georgia to receive regional accreditation.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The ninth and current president since July 2018 is Leocadia I.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Zak, who previously worked as director of the U.S.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] On July 27, 1994, the campus was listed on the National Register of Historic Places as part of the *South Candler Street-Agnes Scott College Historic District*.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The historic district boundaries are East College Ave., South McDonough St., S.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Candler St., East Hill St. and East Davis St.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] It includes the entire campus, as well as historic homes adjacent to the campus.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The campus is also designated by the City of Decatur as a historic district.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The Reverend Frank Henry Gaines served as the first President of Agnes Scott, formally known as Decatur Female Seminary School, for 27 years (1896–1923).
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] During his 27-year presidency, he ensured stability and success for the school, including the transition to the collegiate level, accreditation by the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools, acquisition of 20 acres of land and 21 buildings and an increase in assets from $5,000 to $1.5 million.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott College is located within walking distance of downtown Decatur.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] It is served by Decatur station on the MARTA rail system, which is also a hub for buses, allowing students to travel to the greater Atlanta area.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott occupies more than 90 acres (360,000 m2) in Decatur.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The college also owns the Avery Glen apartments as well as more than a dozen houses in the surrounding neighborhoods housing faculty, staff, and students.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] There are also six dedicated undergraduate dormitories located on campus.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] American poet Robert Frost was first invited to speak at Agnes Scott in 1935, by English professor Emma May Laney, and he visited the college every winter from 1945 until his death in 1963.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] During his visits, he would read poetry in Presser Hall.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] A statue of the poet sculpted by George W.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] A collection of Robert Frost's poetry and letters can be viewed on the second floor of the McCain Library.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, named after Agnes Irvine Scott, is located at the center of "the main loop" and is a one among many Agnes Scott buildings that was listed in the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Main was built in 1891, making it the oldest building on campus.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] This is documented in the history of Agnes Scott by McNair titled *Lest We Forget* published in 1983.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] As technology became more advanced so did Main.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Main Hall was the first building on campus and in the neighborhood to have electric lighting.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Some say that people would gather outside of Main at night just to admire the light shining within the building.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1891, the Gazebo at Agnes Scott college has served a multitude of purposes throughout the years.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] It was originally located in front of Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, however in 1926 it was moved to the west end of Rebekah Scott Hall.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The gazebo has been used as an office, meeting room, meditation chapel, and the Day Student Hut.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1906, Rebekah Scott Hall is the second oldest building remaining at Agnes Scott College.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Rebekah Scott Hall cost $70,000 to build.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] It is named after George Washington Scott's wife, Rebekah Butcher Scott.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The first floor of Rebekah Scott Hall contains offices, the office of financial aid, and the office of admissions.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The second and third floors are used as student housing.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Inman Hall, known commonly as Inman Hall, was built in 1911 and is the oldest building at Agnes Scott College which is used exclusively for student housing.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] In 1985, Inman had major renovations and the third floor was converted into study spaces for students.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] It is made from Indiana limestone and is three stories high.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The building faces west and has a large veranda which stretches along the front of the building.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Jennie D, Inman Hall was gifted to Agnes Scott College by Samuel.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Built in 1923, the Anna Young Alumnae House is dedicated to former science professor and Agnes Scott alumnae, Anna Irwin Young.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Originally the Alumnae House was a central gathering place for ASC alumnae.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The house and bedrooms are now used as a campus guest house.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Behind the house is the Alumnae Garden which houses a statue honoring Robert Frost.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The Anna Young Alumnae House underwent renovations from 2005 until 2009, after which it was re-opened.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The Bradley Observatory at Agnes Scott houses the Beck Telescope, a 30-inch (760 mm) Cassegrain reflector, as well as a planetarium with 70-seat capacity and a radio telescope.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Recently Agnes Scott College and the Georgia Tech Research Institute have collaborated on a project that added a LIDAR facility to the observatory.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The college's science building, the Bullock Science Center, contains a three-story rendering of part of the nucleotide sequence from Agnes Scott's mitochondrial DNA.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The DNA came from a blood sample of an ASC alumna who is a direct descendant of the college's namesake.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott has committed to becoming a carbon-neutral institute by the college's 150th anniversary in 2039 and has taken steps such as partnering with the Clean Air Campaign to reduce its impact on the local environment.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] As of 2015, the college has five solar arrays, four of which are part of Georgia Power's Advanced Solar Initiative.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The fifth array is on the rooftop of the Bradley Observatory and is also used for student research.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The renovation of Campbell Hall into a mixed-use residence hall, learning center, and office space was concluded in 2014 and included installation of a hydro-geothermic HVAC system.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott offers 34 undergraduate majors and 9 graduate and post-baccalaureate programs.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The undergraduate core curriculum SUMMIT focuses on leadership development, global learning, and digital literacy.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] In 2019, Agnes Scott received the Heiskell Award for Scholars as Drivers of Innovation for its SUMMIT curriculum.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Undergraduate students are able to cross-register in other ARCHE member institutions.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The library at Agnes Scott College was an original Carnegie library built in 1910.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] A new library was authorized by the board of trustees in 1935 and opened in the fall of 1936.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] This new library was called the "Carnegie Library" and the original library was turned into a student center.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] It was renamed in 1951 for James McCain, on the occasion of his retirement as the 2nd President of the college.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] As of fall 2025, the student body consists of over 900 undergraduate and graduate students.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Approximately 60% of undergraduates that year were from Georgia.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Given Agnes Scott's emphasis on "mak[ing] lifelong friends, shar[ing] unforgettable experiences, discover[ing] meaningful places and find[ing] belonging in [their] community," a majority of students are encouraged to live on campus.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Thus, most students are expected to live in on-campus housing for all four years as an undergraduate at Agnes Scott College.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] However, the proportion of commuter students has increased (from 15.6 to 18.0 percent between the 2014–2015 and 2019–2020 academic year) due to limited housing caused from an increase in the student population (from 849 to 986 total students) and renovations to the residence halls.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] There are six resident halls situated around the Northern edge of the campus: Winship, Walters, Inman, Rebekah, Campbell, and Agnes Scott Hall (nicknamed "Main").
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] There are over 60 student organizations on campus.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The college hosts several student publications, including *The Silhouette*, the college's yearbook published annually, *The Aurora*, Agnes Scott's literary magazine, and *The Profile,* Agnes Scott newspaper.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott is a member of the National Collegiate Athletic Association Division III which fields six sports teams including basketball, cross country, soccer, softball, tennis, and volleyball.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] All teams compete in the Collegiate Conference of the South (CCS).
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] Agnes Scott was named as one of the Colleges That Change Lives (CTCL).
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The campus has been a filming location for many productions, including the filming location for Windsor College in *Scream 2*, with its campus standing in for the fictional university where Sidney Prescott enrolls to escape her past.
[src:amherst-college/agnes-scott-college] The college's Gothic architecture, particularly Agnes Scott (Main) Hall, provided the backdrop for many scenes, including the gazebo where a key reunion takes place.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] On March 23, 1835, Methodist settlers in Spring Arbor Township obtained a charter for a new seminary from the Michigan Territorial Legislature.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Construction began in 1837 outside Spring Arbor but the Panic of 1837 ended the project.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] A petition to move the seminary to Albion was approved by the legislature in 1839.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Sixty acres (243,000 m2) of land were donated by Jesse Crowell to the renamed "Wesleyan Seminary", and construction began in 1841.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The first classes were held in 1843 in the local Methodist Church.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] In 1844, classes began in the newly constructed Central Building, rebuilt as the present Robinson Hall in 1907.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The "Albion Female Collegiate Institute", founded in 1850, merged in 1857 under the name "The Wesleyan Seminary and Female College at Albion"; the merger was finalized in 1861, under the name "Albion College".
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The legislature authorized the college to confer full four-year college degrees upon both men and women that same year.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion offers bachelor's degrees in business, the humanities, fine arts, natural sciences, and social sciences.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] It provides study-abroad programs in Europe, Latin America, Israel, Africa, Asia, and Australia.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion is perhaps best known for its equestrian center, the Nancy G.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Held Equestrian Center, and its biology and physical education programs.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The three popular first majors, by number of 2021 graduates, were Biology/Biological Sciences (43), Economics (33), and Communication (28).
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The 144-acre (0.58 km2) Whitehouse Nature Center at Albion works with public schools and the community.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] It features six miles of trails, 400 plant species, almost 170 bird species, 25 acres of oak-hickory and flood-plain forest, a tall-grass prairie and spring in the Adele D.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Whitehouse Wildflower Garden, an arboretum of Michigan trees and shrubs, 34 acres of farmland and research projects, and an interpretative building.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion College Astronomical Observatory was built in 1883-84 with encouragement from Samuel Dickie, later the college president.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Since 1990 one student went on to be a Rhodes Scholar, three were Goldwater Scholars, four Truman Scholars and seventeen Fulbright Scholars.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion College is home to the Prentiss M.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Brown Honors Center & Astronomical Observatory, named after Prentiss M.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Representative who graduated from Albion College in 1911.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The observatory is recognized as a Michigan State Historical Site and is used for both educational purposes and public viewing events, allowing students and community members to observe celestial objects such as planets, stars, and solar events.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] One of the notable features of the observatory is the 8.25" Alvan Clark Telescope, which dates back to the late 19th century.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Alvan Clark & Sons were renowned telescope makers and the presence of this telescope adds historical and educational value to the observatory.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] According to "Old Albion", a college history published in 1909, Alvan Clark himself crafted the Albion telescope, marking it as the last telescope he made before his death.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Although this claim remains unverified, Clark's health was declining in the early 1880s and the extent of his work in the years leading up to his death in 1887 is not well-documented.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] As of 2021 Fall enrollment, the student body was 53% female and 47% male.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] 73% of students were Michigan residents, 26% from out-of-state, and 1% from foreign countries.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Ninety-eight percent of students are enrolled full-time.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Prior to the 2010s the enrollment was heavily white and non-low income.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The numbers of black and Hispanic students increased, along with those of first-time university students and lower income students, due to a drive to increase and diversify enrollment.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Between 2013 and 2020, Albion increased its minority enrollment from 18% to 41%, and 48% of the incoming class in 2020 identified as persons of color.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The total cost of attending Albion full time as of 2022 was $67,310.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion offers financial aid of some form to 100% of its students.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The average financial aid package as of December 2022 was $53,714 per student.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion College is home to six social fraternities and as many sororities.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] All are members of the North American Interfraternity Conference and all comprise Albion College's InterFraternity Council (IFC).
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The song "Sweetheart of Sigma Chi" was written in 1911 by Byron D.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Dudleigh Vernor (Albion, 1914), and first performed by Harry Clifford (Albion, 1911) while undergraduates at Albion College.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion College is also home to fifteen honorary, professional, service, and special interest fraternities, including Phi Beta Kappa, established as the Michigan Beta chapter in 1940.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion athletics teams are nicknamed the *Britons*.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The college is a member of the Michigan Intercollegiate Athletic Association (MIAA).
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion has overall won 173 men's MIAA titles (tied for 2nd overall), as well as 26 women's MIAA titles (5th overall).
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] Albion football won the NCAA Division III national championship in 1994.
[src:amherst-college/albion-college] The esports team started in the 2021-2022 academic year.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Albright College traces its founding to 1856 when "Union Seminary" opened.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Present-day Albright was formed by the mergers of several institutions: Albright Collegiate Institute, Central Pennsylvania College, and Schuylkill College.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] "Albright Collegiate Institute" opened in 1895 and was renamed Albright College three years later.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] "Union Seminary", meanwhile, became "Central Pennsylvania College" in 1887 and merged with Albright College in 1902.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] "Schuylkill Seminary", the third institution, was founded in 1881, became "Schuylkill College" in 1923, and merged into Albright in 1928.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Albright's campus relocated from Myerstown, to Schuylkill College's campus, which is the present location of Albright, at the base of Mount Penn in Reading.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The college is named for Pennsylvania-German evangelical preacher Jacob Albright, who founded the Evangelical Association (later known as the Evangelical United Brethren Church).
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Born in 1759 in Douglass Township, (now Montgomery County) with the given name of Johannes Jacob Albrecht, the family changed their surname to "Albright" following Jacob's 1808 death.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] In the late 2010s, enrollment began to decline at the college.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] By 2023, enrollment had declined to 1,652 students, a decline of nearly one-third from what it was in 2010.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] This had significant financial implications for the college which had a $20.3 million deficit in 2023.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] In response, the college laid off 53 employees between 2022 and 2024.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] In late 2024, the college also requested permission to draw a $25 million loan from its $53.1 million dollar endowment.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Shortly thereafter, the college's interim president announced plans to cut two degree programs but also launch several new programs and athletic teams.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] In 2025, the college fired the staff of the Freedman Gallery and sold off the gallery's art collection, including works by Romare Bearden, Elizabeth Catlett, Salvador Dalí, Jasper Johns, Jacob Lawrence, and Robert Rauschenberg.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The move prompted outrage by Albright donors and museum professionals, especially since the sale would do little to help Albright's budgetary problems.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Albright College students are encouraged to cross and combine areas of study without taking longer to graduate.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The college offers Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Science degrees, as well as a Master of Arts and Master of Science degrees in education.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The college also offers online and accelerated degree programs.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Albright offers a wide range of classical and pre-professional programs.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] It created one of the first undergraduate psychobiology programs in the nation in the 1960s.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The college's liberal arts curriculum has a cross-program focus that allows students to create an individualized education.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Fully half of Albright students have concentrations that combine two or three fields of learning.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The theatre program has been honored by the Kennedy Center American College Theater Festival consistently for many years.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] At the National Conference held every April in Washington DC, Albright's theatre program has garnered dozens of awards for distinguished work in performance, direction, dramaturgy, scenic, sound, costume, and lighting design.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Acclaimed productions of "Waiting for Godot" (2007), "Clybourne Park" (2016), "A Raisin in the Sun" (2018) have also been named "Outstanding Production of a Play" – recognizing them as the best college production of their years.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] "A Raisin in the Sun" also received eight other national awards, for distinguished performance, scenic and lighting design, director and performances.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The Albright Creative Research Experience (ACRE) is a multi-disciplinary program that affords undergraduate students the opportunity to conduct research or pursue creative endeavors during the three-week January Interim or summer break.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The students, who work one-on-one with faculty members, can be from any discipline, from STEM subjects to the humanities.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] In 2017, Albright College was named one of the "Best Northeastern" schools by The Princeton Review; this was the fourteenth consecutive year that the college was included in that category.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] News & World Report* ranked the college tied at #146 out of 211 in National Liberal Arts Colleges and tied at #31 in Top Performers on Social Mobility.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] News* ranked Albright 33rd out of 208 national liberal arts colleges in the "Campus Ethnic Diversity" category, and in the "Economic Diversity" category, Albright ranked 27th out of 210 national liberal arts schools.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] *The Economist* magazine listed Albright among the top 50 American colleges and universities for economic value in 2015.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Albright College athletic teams compete in the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) Division III as a member of the Middle Atlantic Conferences.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Charles "Pop" Kelchner founded the men's basketball team in 1900 and was athletic director at Albright College for 21 years.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] He was involved in aspects of Major League Baseball for over 50 years.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Albright College dedicated the baseball field as Kelchner Field in 1952.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Branch Rickey gave the dedication speech, with Connie Mack in attendance.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Kelchner was a graduate of Lafayette College with two degrees and was proficient in German, French, Italian, Spanish, Classical Latin and Greek.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] He served as Professor of Languages and athletic director.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Doggie Julian was the head football coach at Albright from 1929 to 1930.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Biggie Munn was the head football coach at Albright College from 1935 to 1936, before coaching Syracuse University (1946), and most notably Michigan State College (1947–1953), where his 1952 squad won a national championship.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] William "Lone Star" Dietz was the director of athletics and head football coach at Albright from 1937 to 1942.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Dietz led the football team to their first undefeated season in 1937.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] He previously led Washington State to 1916 Rose Bowl victory.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] In the National Football League, Dietz had coached the Boston "Redskins" (1933–1934), the forerunner of the Washington Commanders.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Dietz is in the Albright College Athletic Hall of Fame and the College Football Hall of Fame.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] In 1948, the University of Maryland Eastern Shore (UMES) and Albright College played the first intercollegiate football game between an Historically Black Colleges and Universities (HBCU) institution and a majority-white institution.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The Philadelphia Eagles held preseason training camp at Albright from 1968 through 1972.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Renken was athletic director and basketball head coach for 38 consecutive seasons.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] A highly regarded figure in collegiate athletics in general and specifically basketball, Renken was the president of the United States Olympic Basketball Team Selection Committee for the 1976 Olympic Games.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] He also served as the president of the National Association of Basketball Coaches (NABC) in 1979–1980.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Durante, however, declined reinstatement, citing his former teammates' stated lack of trust in him.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] Albright's campus radio station, WXAC 91.3 FM is a student-operated college radio station.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] The initial call name was WALC, but was later changed to WXAC on March 8, 1965.
[src:amherst-college/albright-college] WALC had been the same call name for the Alcoa Steamship Lines.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Alexander Meiklejohn was born on 3 February 1872, in Newbold Street, Rochdale, Lancashire, England.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He was of Scottish descent, and the youngest of eight sons.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] When he was eight, the family moved to the United States, settling in Rhode Island.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Family members pooled their money to send him to school.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He earned bachelor's and master's degrees at Brown University, graduating Phi Beta Kappa, and completed his doctorate in philosophy at Cornell in 1897.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] At Brown, he was a member of Theta Delta Chi.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] In 1897, Meiklejohn began teaching at Brown.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] In 1901, he became second dean of the university, a position he held for twelve years.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] The first-year advising program at Brown bears his name.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] From 1912 to 1923, Meiklejohn served as president of Amherst College.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] His presidency ended with his forced resignation for trying to apply his reforms, and thirteen students refused their diplomas that year in protest.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Although he was offered the presidency of other colleges, Meiklejohn proposed to open a new, experimental liberal arts college.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He was unable to develop adequate funding for creating an entirely new school, but he was invited by Glenn Frank, new president of the University of Wisconsin, to create the University of Wisconsin Experimental College there, which ran from 1927 to 1932.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He retired from the University of Wisconsin in 1938, having already moved to Berkeley, California.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He was a cofounder of the School of Social Studies in San Francisco, an adult education program focusing on "great books" and American democracy.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] In 1965, Ann Fagan Ginger, an American attorney and activist, founded an institute to advance human rights and peace law through legal research, education, and advocacy, and named it Meiklejohn Civil Liberties Institute (MCLI), with Meiklejohn's permission.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] In 1945, Meiklejohn was a U.S. delegate to the founding meeting of UNESCO in London.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn died at age 92 on 17 December 1964, in Berkeley, California.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn was known as an advocate of First Amendment freedoms and was a member of the National Committee of the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU).
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He was a notable proponent of the link between freedom of speech and democracy.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He argued that the concept of democracy is that of self-government by the people.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] For such a system to work an informed electorate is necessary.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] To be appropriately knowledgeable, there must be no constraints on the free flow of information and ideas.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] According to Meiklejohn, democracy will not be true to its essential ideal if those in power are able to manipulate the electorate by withholding information and stifling criticism.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn acknowledges that the desire to manipulate opinion can stem from the motive of seeking to benefit society.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] However, he argues, choosing manipulation negates, in its means, the democratic ideal.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Eric Barendt has called the defense of free speech on the grounds of democracy "probably the most attractive and certainly the most fashionable free speech theory in modern Western democracies".
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn's 1948 article, "Free Speech and Its Relation to Self-Government," was cited by Justice Breyer in a concurring opinion for *Nixon v.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn was a supporter of the Fair Play for Cuba Committee.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] The American Association of University Professors (AAUP) established the Alexander Meiklejohn Freedom Award to honor his work.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] He received the Rosenberger Medal in 1959.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Kennedy to receive the Presidential Medal of Freedom, which was presented by Lyndon B.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn has been honored with a number of programs or institution named after him, including the Meiklejohn Civil Liberties Institute (MCLI) in Berkeley.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] The Meiklejohn Advising Program is Brown University's advising program for incoming first-year students.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn Advisors (known as Meiklejohns or Micks for short) are student advisors who are paired with each first-year, along with a faculty advisor, to provide academic advice and help the transition to college.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] The University of Wisconsin–Madison's Meiklejohn House (home to the Integrated Liberal Studies program) continues to espouse the ideals of Meiklejohn's experimental college by engaging students in interdisciplinary liberal education.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn Hall at the California State University, East Bay, houses many of the school's liberal arts programs.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] The Evergreen State College in Olympia, Washington, was deeply influenced by Meiklejohn's pedagogical philosophy during its founding and maintains many of his central principles today.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] Meiklejohn Fellows Program at Amherst College is a unique program reserved for first-generation and/or low-income students.
[src:amherst-college/alexander-meiklejohn] The program provides dedicated advising, programming, peer-to-peer support, and summer internship funding.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst is an exclusively undergraduate four-year institution.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] 1,914 full-time students were enrolled in fall 2024.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Students choose courses from 42 major programs in an open curriculum and are not required to study a core curriculum or fulfill any distribution requirements; students may also design their own interdisciplinary major.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst competes in the NCAA Division III as a member of the New England Small College Athletic Conference.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst has historically had close relationships and rivalries with Williams College and Wesleyan University, which form the Little Three colleges.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The college is also a member of the Five College Consortium, which allows its students to attend classes at four other Pioneer Valley institutions: Mount Holyoke College, Smith College, Hampshire College, and the University of Massachusetts Amherst.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 1812, funds were raised in Amherst for a secondary school, Amherst Academy; it opened December 1814.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The academy incorporated in 1816, and eventually counted among its students Emily Dickinson, Sylvester Graham, and Mary Lyon (founder of Mount Holyoke College).
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The institution was named after the town, which in turn had been named after Jeffery, Lord Amherst, a veteran from the Seven Years' War and later commanding general of the British forces in North America.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] On November 18, 1817, a project was adopted at the Academy to raise funds for the free instruction of "indigent young men of promising talents and hopeful piety, who shall manifest a desire to obtain a liberal education with a sole view to the Christian ministry".
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] This required a substantial investment from benefactors.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] During the fundraising for the project, it became clear that without larger designs, it would be impossible to raise sufficient funds.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] This led the committee overseeing the project to conclude that a new institution should be created.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] On August 18, 1818, the Amherst Academy board of trustees accepted this conclusion and began building a new college.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Founded in 1821, Amherst College developed from Amherst Academy, first established as a secondary school.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The college was originally suggested as an alternative to Williams College, which was struggling to stay open.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Although Williams survived, Amherst was formed and developed as a distinct institution.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Moore, then President of Williams College, however, still believed that Williamstown was an unsuitable location for a college.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] When Amherst College was established, he was elected its first president on May 8, 1821.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] At its opening, Amherst had forty-seven students.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Fifteen of these had followed Moore from Williams College.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Those fifteen represented about one-third of the total students at Amherst, and about one-fifth of the whole number in the three classes to which they belonged in Williams College.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] President Moore died on June 29, 1823, and was replaced with a Williams College trustee, Heman Humphrey.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Williams alumni are fond of an apocryphal story ascribing the removal of books from the Williams College library to Amherst College.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Payne declared the story false, but many still nurture the legend.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 1826, Edward Jones became Amherst's first Black graduate.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst grew quickly, and for two years in the mid-1830s, it was the second largest college in the United States, behind Yale.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 1835, Amherst attempted to create a course of study parallel to the classical liberal arts education.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] This parallel course focused less on Greek and Latin, instead emphasizing contemporary English, French, and Spanish languages, chemistry, economics, etc.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The parallel course did not take hold and replace the classical until the next century.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst was founded as a non-sectarian institution "for the classical education of indigent young men of piety and talents for the Christian ministry" (Tyler, *A History of Amherst College*).
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] One of the hallmarks of the new college was its Charity Fund, an early form of financial aid that paid the tuition of poorer students.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Although officially non-denominational, Amherst was considered a religiously conservative institution with a strong connection to Calvinism; the Puritans still controlled much of Massachusetts life.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] As a result, there was considerable debate in the Massachusetts government over whether the new college should receive an official charter from the state.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] A charter was not granted until February 21, 1825, as reflected on the Amherst seal.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Religious conservatism persisted at Amherst until the mid-nineteenth century: students who consumed alcohol or played cards were subject to expulsion.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] A number of religious revivals were held at Amherst.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Toward the end of the nineteenth century, however, the college began a transition toward secularism.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] This movement was considered to culminate in the 1949 demolition of the college church.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Academic hoods in the United States are traditionally lined with the official colors of the school, in theory so watchers can tell where the hood wearer earned his or her degree.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst's hoods are purple (Williams' official color) with a white stripe or chevron, said to signify that Amherst was born of Williams.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst records one of the first uses of Latin honors of any American college, dating back to 1881.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The college was an all-male school until the late 1960s, when a few female students from nearby schools in the Four-College Consortium (Amherst, Mount Holyoke, Smith, UMass) attended on an experimental basis.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In October 1974, the faculty voted in favor of coeducation and in November 1974, the board of trustees voted to admit female students starting in the 1975–1976 school year.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] This was done while John William Ward served as president.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 1975, nine women who were already attending classes as part of an inter-college exchange program were admitted as transfer students.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In June 1976, they became the first female graduates of the college.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The college established the Black Studies Department in 1969.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 1973, it launched the nation's first undergraduate neuroscience program.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 1983, it established a Department of Asian Languages and Literatures, which was later to become the Department of Asian Languages and Civilizations.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 1984, on-campus fraternities were abolished.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The former fraternity buildings, which were owned by the college, were converted into residence halls.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The Department of Women's and Gender Studies, which later became the Department of Sexuality, Women's, and Gender Studies, was established in 1987, and the Department of Law, Jurisprudence, and Social Thought in 1993.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In March 2013, the faculty adopted an open-access policy.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Eight years later, the college ended its practice of legacy admissions and increased financial aid to increase access to low and middle-income students and diversify the college.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst College is located in the town of Amherst in Western Massachusetts.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst College has a total of 34 residence halls, seven of which are strictly for first year students.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Following their first year, sophomores, juniors, and seniors have the choice to live off campus and are offered options of Themed Houses including Arts House, Russian House, and French House, however this option is only available for two years of residence.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] First-year students are required to live on campus.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The college also owns the Emily Dickinson Museum, operated as a museum about the life and history of poet Emily Dickinson, and the Inn on Boltwood near to the main campus.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst College is reducing its energy consumption through a computerized monitoring system for lighting and the use of an efficient cogeneration facility.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The cogeneration facility features a gas turbine that generates electricity in addition to steam for heating the campus.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst also operates a composting program, in which a portion of the food waste from dining halls is sent to a farmer in Vermont.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst College offers 41 fields of study (with 850+ courses) in the sciences, arts, humanities, mathematics and computer sciences, social sciences, foreign languages, classics, and several interdisciplinary fields (including premedical studies) and provides an unusually open curriculum.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Students are not required to study a core curriculum or fulfill any distribution requirements and may even design their own unique interdisciplinary major.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Freshmen may take advanced courses, and seniors may take introductory ones.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst College is accredited by the New England Commission of Higher Education.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Forty-five percent of Amherst students in the class of 2019 were double majors.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst College has been the first college to have undergraduate departments in the interdisciplinary fields of American Studies; Law, Jurisprudence and Social Thought; and Neuroscience and has helped to pioneer other interdisciplinary programs, including Asian Languages and Civilizations.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The Amherst library is named for long-time faculty member, poet Robert Frost.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The student-faculty ratio is 7:1 and 84% of classes have fewer than 30 students.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Notable faculty members include, among others, modern literature and poetry critic William H.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] News & World Report* rankings in 1987, Amherst College has been ranked ten times as the first overall among 266 liberal arts colleges in the United States, and in 2022 ranked second, behind Williams.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 2023, Amherst College was ranked as the best liberal arts college and 8th best college or university overall in the United States by The WSJ/College Pulse 2024 Best College Rankings.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 2022, Amherst was ranked as the best liberal arts college in the country by *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] *Forbes* ranked Amherst College as the 24th best college or university in the United States for their 2024–25 rankings and the 16th best college or university in the United States in 2021.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst ranked 6th in the 2021 *Washington Monthly* liberal arts college rankings, which focus on contribution to the public good in three broad categories: social mobility, research, and promoting public service.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The issue arose when a group of alumni petitioned the college trustees and President Biddy Martin to "dissociate the institution" from Arkes's "divisive and destructive" views, focusing particularly on his May 2013 comparison of homosexuality to bestiality, pedophilia and necrophilia.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Martin disagreed, citing past debates over the college's position on the Vietnam War and apartheid in South Africa—issues on which the college initially remained silent but eventually took a public position.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In such times, she said, colleges should "avoid taking institutional positions on controversial political matters, except in extraordinary circumstances" and should simultaneously both "protect their communities from discrimination and disrespect" and "cherish a diversity of viewpoints".
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst is a member of the Five Colleges consortium, which allows its students to attend classes at four other Pioneer Valley institutions.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] These include Mount Holyoke College, Smith College, Hampshire College, and the University of Massachusetts Amherst.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In addition to the 850 courses available on campus, Amherst students have an additional 5,300 classes to consider through the Consortium (without paying additional tuition) and access to 8 million library volumes.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The Five Colleges are geographically close to one another and are linked by buses that run between the campuses.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The Five Colleges share resources and develop common academic programs.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Museums10 is a consortium of local art, history and science museums.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The Five College Dance Department is one of the largest in the nation.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The joint Astronomy department shares use of the Five College Radio Astronomy Observatory, which contributed to work that won the 1993 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The Five College Coastal and Marine Sciences Program offers an interdisciplinary curriculum to undergraduates in the Five Colleges.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Despite its high cost of attendance – the comprehensive tuition, room, and board fee for the 2026–27 academic year was $96,360 – Amherst College meets the full demonstrated need of every admitted student.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Roughly sixty percent of current students receive scholarship aid, and the average financial aid package award amounts to $84,590; college expenditures are approximately $140,000 per student each year.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In July 2007, Amherst announced that grants would replace loans in all financial aid packages beginning in the 2008–09 academic year.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst had already been the first school to eliminate loans for low-income students, and with this announcement it joined Princeton University, Cornell University and Davidson College, then the only colleges to eliminate loans from need-based financial aid packages.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Increased rates of admission of highly qualified lower income students has resulted in greater equality of opportunity at Amherst than is usual at elite American colleges.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In the 2008–2009 academic year, Amherst College also extended its need-blind admission policy to international applicants.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 2021, it also eliminated preferences for students whose parents are alumni ("legacies").
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst's resources, faculty, and academic life allow the college to enroll students with a range of talents, interests, and commitments.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Students represent 48 states, the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, and sixty-six countries.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The median family income of Amherst students is $158,200, with 51% of students coming from the top 10% highest-earning families and 24% from the bottom 60%.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Ninety-eight percent of students live on campus.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Ninety-eight percent of Amherst freshmen enrolled in Fall 2020 returned for their sophomore year; ninety-two percent of the most recent cohort graduated within six years.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] There are more than 200 student groups at Amherst.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] More than a third of the student body are members of a varsity athletics team.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Students pursue their interests through student-led organizations funded by a student fee and distributed by the student government, including a variety of cultural and religious groups, publications, fine and performing arts and political advocacy and service groups.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Groups include a medieval sword-fighting club, a knitting club, and a club devoted to random acts of kindness, among others.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Community service groups and opportunities (locally—through the Center for Community Engagement, nationally, and internationally) have been a priority at Amherst and for former President Anthony Marx, who helped start a secondary school for black students in apartheid South Africa.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] One of the longstanding traditions at the college involves the *Sabrina* statue.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Even year and odd year classes battle for possession of the historic statue, often engaging in elaborate pranks in the process.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 2012, President Biddy Martin began a community-wide review of the sexual misconduct and disciplinary policies at the college.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] This review was sparked by several factors, including an underground fraternity's T-shirt design that critics alleged was misogynist and an essay by Angie Epifano published in *The Amherst Student*, wherein she accused the college of inappropriate handling of a case of sexual assault.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In January 2013, a college committee published a report noting Amherst's rate of sexual assault as similar to other colleges and universities, and making recommendations to address the problem.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In May 2014, the Amherst board of trustees banned students from joining any underground or off-campus fraternity.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] After a complaint was filed by Epifano and an anonymous former student in November 2013, the US Department of Education opened an investigation into the college's handling of sexual violence and potential violations of Title IX.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In May 2014, the Department of Education announced a list of 55 colleges and universities (including Amherst) currently under investigation.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] A report from Amherst College stated that 2009 to 2011, Amherst reported 35 instances of "forcible sex offenses", a term that encompasses rape, attempted rape, and lesser forms of sexual contact.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In 2022, in response to the anonymous sharing of sexual assault experiences at Amherst College on the Instagram account @amherstshareyourstory, then President Biddy Martin announced the launch of a new comprehensive review of the issue of sexual misconduct and assault on campus.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] According to the 2023 NECHE Interim Crediting Report listening sessions and interviews were conducted, and a website for anonymous reporting of concerns was created.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The NECHE interim report also suggested that the review was expected to be published in Spring 2023.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] However currently there has been no update or public disclosure of the 2022 review.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In the second decade of the 21st century, the original unofficial mascot of Amherst College, Lord Jeffery Amherst, became a cause of concern in the Amherst community.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Many sought to separate the school from the problematic legacy of Lord Jeffery Amherst, in particular his advocacy of the use of biological warfare against Native Americans.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In May 2014, after a wild moose found its way onto the Amherst College campus and into the backyard of the house of the college president, students organized a Facebook campaign to change the mascot of the school to a moose.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The page grew rapidly in popularity, receiving over 900 "likes" in under two weeks, and inspiring both a Twitter and Tumblr account for the newly proposed mascot.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] At the Commencement ceremony for the class of 2014, the moose mascot was mentioned by Biddy Martin in her address, and the Dining Hall served Moose Tracks ice cream in front of an ice sculpture of a moose.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In February 2015, discussion of a mascot change continued when the editorial board of the *Amherst Student*, the college's official student-run newspaper, came out in favor of "the moose-scot".
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In November 2015 the student body and the faculty overwhelmingly voted to vacate the mascot.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] That same month, several hundred students who staged a sit-in protest against racism at the college library included among their demands a call for the college to cease use of the Lord Jeff mascot.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The decision to drop the mascot was made official by the college's trustees on January 26, 2016.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] In April 2017, Amherst announced that their official mascot would be the mammoth.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Mammoths beat the other finalists "Valley Hawks", "Purple and White", "Wolves", and "Fighting Poets" in a ranked-choice election process.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The mammoth is linked to Amherst due to the long-standing presence of a Columbian Mammoth skeleton on display in the Beneski Museum of Natural History on campus, which dated back to the 1920s excavation of the skeleton by Amherst professor Frederic Brewster Loomis in Melbourne, Florida.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst participates in the NCAA's Division III, the Eastern College Athletic Conference, and the New England Small College Athletic Conference, which includes Bates, Bowdoin, Colby, Connecticut College, Hamilton, Middlebury, Trinity, Tufts, Wesleyan, and Williams.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst is also one of the "Little Three", along with Williams and Wesleyan.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] A Little Three champion is informally recognized by most teams based on the head-to-head records of the three schools, but three-way competitions are held in some of the sports.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst claims its athletics program as the oldest in the nation, pointing to its compulsory physical fitness regimen put in place in 1860 (the mandate that all students participate in sports or pursue physical education has been discontinued).
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst and Williams played the first college baseball game July 2, 1859.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Athletic skill plays a factor in the admissions decisions of between 28% and 35% of each incoming class.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Amherst fields several club athletic teams, including ultimate, soccer, crew, rugby union, water polo, equestrian, mountain biking, fencing, sailing and skiing.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Intramural sports include soccer, tennis, golf, basketball, volleyball and softball.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] The sport of Ultimate was started and named at Amherst College in the mid-1960s by Jared Kass.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] President, the current Sovereign Prince of Monaco, two Prime Ministers and one Foreign Minister of Greece, a President of Kenya, a President of El Salvador, a Chief Justice of the United States, three Speakers of the U.S.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Poet Laureate, the legal architect of *Brown v.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Among its alumni, faculty and affiliates are six Nobel Prize laureates and twenty Rhodes Scholars.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] President Calvin Coolidge, Chief Justice Harlan F.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] Stone, and other notable writers, academics, politicians, entertainers, businesspeople, and activists have been graduates as well.
[src:amherst-college/amherst-college] There are approximately 23,000 living alumni, of whom about 45% make a gift to Amherst each year—one of the highest alumni participation rates of any college in the country.
